<TopicInfo Title="Equation Systems" Subtitle="Solve linear and non-linear systems">
    <div>
        <p class="topic-info__overview">
            A system of $n$ equations in $n$ unknowns. Linear systems have a unique
            solution when the coefficient matrix is non-singular. Non-linear systems
            require iterative methods starting from an initial guess.
        </p>

        <div class="topic-info__cards">
            <div class="topic-info__card">
                <h3>Cramer's Rule</h3>
                <div class="topic-info__formula">$$x_i = \frac{\det(A_i)}{\det(A)}$$</div>
                <p>Expresses each unknown as a ratio of determinants. Exact for small systems
                but $O(n!)$ complexity makes it impractical beyond $n \approx 4$.</p>
                <p class="topic-info__limitation">Fails when $\det(A) = 0$ (singular matrix).</p>
            </div>

            <div class="topic-info__card">
                <h3>Gaussian Elimination</h3>
                <div class="topic-info__formula">$$A\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{b} \xrightarrow{\text{row ops}} U\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{c}$$</div>
                <p>Reduces the augmented matrix $[A|\mathbf{b}]$ to upper-triangular form with
                partial pivoting, then back-substitutes. $O(n^3)$ — the standard workhorse.</p>
                <p class="topic-info__limitation">Numerical instability without pivoting; fails on singular systems.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="topic-info__card">
                <h3>Fixed-Point Iteration</h3>
                <div class="topic-info__formula">$$\mathbf{x}^{(k+1)} = \mathbf{g}(\mathbf{x}^{(k)})$$</div>
                <p>Rewrites each equation as $x_i = g_i(\mathbf{x})$ and iterates from an
                initial guess. Converges when the spectral radius $\rho(J_g) &lt; 1$.</p>
                <p class="topic-info__limitation">Convergence is not guaranteed; sensitive to initial guess and formulation.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="topic-info__card">
                <h3>Gauss-Seidel</h3>
                <div class="topic-info__formula">$$x_i^{(k+1)} = g_i\!\left(x_1^{(k+1)},\ldots,x_{i-1}^{(k+1)},x_i^{(k)},\ldots\right)$$</div>
                <p>Like fixed-point but immediately uses freshly computed values within each
                sweep. Typically converges faster than Jacobi-style fixed-point iteration.</p>
                <p class="topic-info__limitation">Convergence not guaranteed for all systems; requires diagonally dominant or similar structure.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</TopicInfo>